00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.670
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:24.970
&gt;&gt; James Wintle: Okay, so
my name is James Wintle.

00:00:24.970 --> 00:00:29.940
I am a reference librarian here
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:29.940 --> 00:00:36.330
And what I, I had a bit of
a change of heart recently

00:00:36.330 --> 00:00:39.900
about what exactly I was
going to do in this program.

00:00:41.110 --> 00:00:45.350
Initially, I was going to
give a moderately interesting,

00:00:45.350 --> 00:00:47.450
but possibly boring lecture
about persil [phonetic].

00:00:47.450 --> 00:00:55.440 position:56%
And as I was researching the history
of early music at the Library

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:58.730
of Congress and the performances
of early music at the Library

00:00:58.730 --> 00:01:03.090
of Congress, I came
across something of a gem.

00:01:03.090 --> 00:01:08.220
And that particular gem
happened on, yes you guessed it,

00:01:08.220 --> 00:01:11.430
November 29th and 30th in 1962.

00:01:11.430 --> 00:01:16.770 position:56%
And what happened on that particular
day, or evening as it were,

00:01:16.770 --> 00:01:21.200
is that the actor Basil Rathbone,

00:01:21.200 --> 00:01:26.650
yes the perplexed looks are
appropriate, came to the library,

00:01:26.650 --> 00:01:32.590
and with an Elizabethan broken
consort, gave a performance

00:01:32.590 --> 00:01:36.200
in which he read Elizabethan
poetry and monologues

00:01:36.200 --> 00:01:42.650 position:56%
from Shakespeare's plays,
interspersed with Elizabethan music.

00:01:42.650 --> 00:01:46.320
And it's quite stunning and quite
interesting, and not the sort

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:49.640
of thing that one hears
these days at all.

00:01:49.640 --> 00:01:55.620
So I decided to cast off
my delusions of grandeur

00:01:55.620 --> 00:01:59.970 position:56%
about giving a personal lecture, and
let everyone hear this thing that is

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:02.820
so unique and so interesting
and something

00:02:02.820 --> 00:02:06.010
that really just would
not happen were it not

00:02:06.010 --> 00:02:07.860
for the Library of Congress.

00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:15.790
The concert series here is a bit of
a unique animal in and of itself,

00:02:15.790 --> 00:02:20.110
and every once in a while, we have
these performances that really,

00:02:20.110 --> 00:02:23.390
you just couldn't, you just
couldn't get anywhere else

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:27.020
because no other concert series
is also associated with the Center

00:02:27.020 --> 00:02:31.020
for Poetry that can co-sponsor
such a thing and put it on.

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:35.710
So I wanted to give
everyone a unique experience

00:02:35.710 --> 00:02:39.160
that you really just couldn't get
everywhere else, or anywhere else.

00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:41.770
And encourage you to go read
more about persil [phonetic]

00:02:41.770 --> 00:02:44.220
and you'll probably hear all
the boring stuff I was going

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:45.720
to say anyway.

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:48.970
So, that being said, just a little
bit about the concert series,

00:02:48.970 --> 00:02:51.520
for those of you who don't know,

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:54.940
we're celebrating the 90th
anniversary of concert series.

00:02:54.940 --> 00:03:04.550
It was founded in 1925 by
the, under the patronage

00:03:04.550 --> 00:03:08.930
of Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge who
had had a chamber music festival

00:03:08.930 --> 00:03:17.530
in the Berkshires, and wanted her
work as a chamber music patron

00:03:17.530 --> 00:03:20.050
to live on after her death.

00:03:20.050 --> 00:03:23.780
And decided that in order to
do that, she needed to partner

00:03:23.780 --> 00:03:28.010
with a cultural institution
that had the longevity

00:03:28.010 --> 00:03:32.180
that a person obviously
doesn't have.

00:03:32.180 --> 00:03:35.480
So she picked the Library
of Congress, she was friends

00:03:35.480 --> 00:03:38.280
with the person who was the
head of the music division

00:03:38.280 --> 00:03:39.980
at that time, Carl Engel.

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:41.280
And many of you have
heard this before,

00:03:41.280 --> 00:03:45.340
but I'll just give this little
overview for those you who haven't.

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:51.290 position:56%
She was friends with Carl Engel and
her partnership with him enabled her

00:03:51.290 --> 00:03:57.160
to work out the details, to donate
money to build the auditorium

00:03:57.160 --> 00:04:00.410
in which you're going to hear
the concert this evening.

00:04:00.410 --> 00:04:05.580
And there was famously an act of
Congress that had to be passed

00:04:05.580 --> 00:04:08.750
in order for that to happen
because it was unprecedented

00:04:08.750 --> 00:04:12.000
that someone would donate a large
amount of money to the government

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.220
for a building project just

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:17.470
because they felt it was
the right thing to do.

00:04:17.470 --> 00:04:19.640
That sort of thing just
didn't really happen,

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:21.390
and still doesn't really happen.

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:25.260
And so we have this beautiful
chamber music auditorium thanks

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:28.590
to the generosity of
Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge.

00:04:28.590 --> 00:04:33.780 position:56%
And she is someone that we like to
remember often in the music division

00:04:33.780 --> 00:04:37.900
because she sponsored so
many wonderful commissions.

00:04:37.900 --> 00:04:44.240
Especially mid 20th century, she
was commissioning great works

00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:47.920
from Aaron Copland, from Bela
Bartok, from Arnold Schoenberg,

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:51.520
from basically any
composer that you can think

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:53.780
of that really made an impact.

00:04:53.780 --> 00:04:58.630
Prokofiev, you know, just everyone
was writing music to be performed

00:04:58.630 --> 00:05:03.770
in this hall and we continue
that tradition today.

00:05:03.770 --> 00:05:07.060
This season I think there are six
new premiers, it's in the booklet.

00:05:07.060 --> 00:05:09.650
You can check my facts on that.

00:05:09.650 --> 00:05:14.270
But it's a wonderful series,
and giving a little history

00:05:14.270 --> 00:05:17.290
of that series I thought
was important,

00:05:17.290 --> 00:05:20.410
particularly as it
regards early music.

00:05:20.410 --> 00:05:23.040
Because there have been
so many commissions

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:26.580
and so many important commissions
that have been premiered here,

00:05:26.580 --> 00:05:28.250
and new works that have
been premiered here.

00:05:28.250 --> 00:05:31.840
It is often forgotten that
even from the beginning,

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:33.640
the beginning of this
concert series,

00:05:33.640 --> 00:05:36.250
early music was very
much a part of it.

00:05:36.250 --> 00:05:39.750
And there have been
concerts, a number of concerts

00:05:39.750 --> 00:05:43.490
over the years by, for
insistence, the New York Pro Musica

00:05:43.490 --> 00:05:45.710
with Noah Greenberg
has done medieval

00:05:45.710 --> 00:05:48.450
and renaissance music
here a number of times.

00:05:48.450 --> 00:05:52.140
Alfred Deller famously gave a
recital here in the late fifties.

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:59.500
And Mrs. Coolidge not only
commissioned new works,

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:04.780
but also commissioned
modernizations of early music.

00:06:04.780 --> 00:06:07.560
And these are things that we,

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:11.090
I mean I've never actually
heard them performed,

00:06:11.090 --> 00:06:14.310
but if they could be
performed sometime,

00:06:14.310 --> 00:06:17.250
they will be performed here,
not anyplace else, I'm sure.

00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:21.620
But there are, there are these
little corners of the collection

00:06:21.620 --> 00:06:24.200
of manuscripts that she
donated to the library.

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:30.350
Like for example, orchestrations of
the luli arias [assumed spelling],

00:06:30.350 --> 00:06:33.300 position:56%
by the American composer Roy Harris.

00:06:33.300 --> 00:06:37.300
Who she commissioned to orchestrate
these luli arias [assumed spelling]

00:06:37.300 --> 00:06:41.270
for a performance in
the Coolidge auditorium.

00:06:41.270 --> 00:06:45.490
And so the co-mingling of early
and modern music is something

00:06:45.490 --> 00:06:47.670
that has a strong history here.

00:06:47.670 --> 00:06:53.250
And it's the early part of it
that we will enjoy this evening,

00:06:53.250 --> 00:06:58.590
first in this concert,
and then of course

00:06:58.590 --> 00:07:02.720
with [inaudible] singing a
beautiful, beautiful program.

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:05.960
So what we will deal with
today crosses over a bit

00:07:05.960 --> 00:07:08.310
with the earliest part
of her program.

00:07:08.310 --> 00:07:13.580
And we're going to be listening to,
in particular, Elizabethan music.

00:07:13.580 --> 00:07:15.650
And many of you, I'm sure,

00:07:15.650 --> 00:07:21.610
know Elizabeth the first was
quite an active lover and patron

00:07:21.610 --> 00:07:25.400
of music herself, and
was quite a good dancer.

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:30.520
And the idea of, or the corpus
of dance music that came

00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:38.190
out of her reign was quite
spectacular, as well as wonderful,

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:40.440
you know, sacred music and
all the other things that we,

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:42.610
that we hear from that time.

00:07:42.610 --> 00:07:44.930
One of the great composers
of the day, who we're going

00:07:44.930 --> 00:07:49.190
to hear later this
evening, was John Dowland.

00:07:49.190 --> 00:07:53.090
And he is featured on the
program we're going here

00:07:53.090 --> 00:07:56.190
in just a moment as well.

00:07:56.190 --> 00:08:02.220
He was not, he was a very, he
was a very well-known composer

00:08:02.220 --> 00:08:05.950
particularly in England,
particularly in Europe,

00:08:05.950 --> 00:08:11.240
but never was able to get a
position at the Elizabethan court.

00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:15.930
So he was constantly
striving to gain the attention

00:08:15.930 --> 00:08:18.340
of Elizabeth and of the court.

00:08:18.340 --> 00:08:22.330
And so when you hear pieces on
the program tonight like the Earl

00:08:22.330 --> 00:08:26.830
of Essex Galliard, it's turned
into a song and different pieces

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:31.770
by Dowland that have a little
bit of a political bench to them.

00:08:31.770 --> 00:08:34.720
It's because he is trying
to gain that attention.

00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:39.630
And he worked actually in
Denmark for Christian the fourth,

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:43.190
but published all of
his music in London.

00:08:43.190 --> 00:08:46.990
And that is the real telling
element of his career,

00:08:46.990 --> 00:08:49.510
that even though he was
working in Europe, he made the,

00:08:49.510 --> 00:08:52.790
he made the trip, he made
the effort to come to England

00:08:52.790 --> 00:08:55.110
and publish his works there

00:08:55.110 --> 00:08:57.770
so they would be disseminated
amongst the people

00:08:57.770 --> 00:09:01.720
and become the popular music
of the day that it really was.

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:05.910
And people talk about John
Dowland as being a kind

00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:09.050
of folk musician of his day.

00:09:09.050 --> 00:09:12.140
And it really is true, even though
he was writing very sophisticated

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:14.330 position:56%
music, he was writing popular music.

00:09:14.330 --> 00:09:16.170
And that's something that
a lot of people, I think,

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:20.270
have lost because we today, think
of concert music as one thing

00:09:20.270 --> 00:09:22.050
and popular music as another.

00:09:22.050 --> 00:09:27.020
When in fact, that's only something
that has happened in the past,

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:34.790 position:56%
you know, hundred years, hundred and
fifty years really, that the music

00:09:34.790 --> 00:09:38.580
that important composers were
writing was not really thought

00:09:38.580 --> 00:09:41.050
of as popular, but in
the Elizabethan era,

00:09:41.050 --> 00:09:42.740
it's very much that way.

00:09:42.740 --> 00:09:46.590
And so, if you look at your
program and you think, oh well,

00:09:46.590 --> 00:09:49.090
why is there, why are
there these pieces by Simon

00:09:49.090 --> 00:09:52.880
and Garfunkel at the end, right?

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:56.660
It is in fact because that
is the modern equivalent

00:09:56.660 --> 00:09:59.350
of what John Downland was
doing in the Elizabethan era,

00:09:59.350 --> 00:10:04.740
much more so then songs
by, you know,

00:10:04.740 --> 00:10:08.430
John Adams, or something like that.

00:10:08.430 --> 00:10:13.620
It's, it really is that, that one,
that side of what Dowland was doing

00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:15.500
that is important to represent
and important to remember.

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:18.320
So that will happen
later, that being said.

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:23.260
The pieces on this program
are for broken consort.

00:10:23.260 --> 00:10:27.090
And that is not a reference to the
fact that the lute was very easy

00:10:27.090 --> 00:10:30.990
to break, when in fact it was.

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:35.530
But, a broken consort is
a group of instruments

00:10:35.530 --> 00:10:37.860
that are not all of the same kind.

00:10:37.860 --> 00:10:42.860
A consort of instruments,
in the Elizabethan parlance,

00:10:42.860 --> 00:10:46.130
is a group of different size
instruments of the same kind.

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:49.060
For instance, a consort of
recorders, a consort of lutes.

00:10:49.060 --> 00:10:53.190
There were treble lutes, there
were bass lutes, and in between.

00:10:53.190 --> 00:11:00.120
But a broken consort which became
a standard instrumentation was a

00:11:00.120 --> 00:11:02.120
little bit of a few things.

00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:05.110
It was a treble viol,
and a bass viol.

00:11:05.110 --> 00:11:10.960
A treble viol, bass viol,
lute, this is the dulcian

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:13.300
which could be doubled as a flute.

00:11:13.300 --> 00:11:16.620
This is actually a, no it's not
a dulcian, it's a bass recorder.

00:11:16.620 --> 00:11:19.180
So it could be either
one of those recorders.

00:11:19.180 --> 00:11:24.600
This is a bandora which
was also called pandora.

00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:29.190
If anybody listens to an app called
Pandora, you have your music on it,

00:11:29.190 --> 00:11:31.250
you can think of bass
string instruments

00:11:31.250 --> 00:11:34.640
from the Elizabethan era the
next time you turn it on.

00:11:34.640 --> 00:11:40.670
But the pandora or bandora,
and this was basically a bass

00:11:40.670 --> 00:11:42.160
lute-like instrument.

00:11:42.160 --> 00:11:44.680
The cittern, which looks
quite a lot like a mandolin,

00:11:44.680 --> 00:11:46.750
except it has this
curved head on it.

00:11:46.750 --> 00:11:52.840
And the cittern is interesting
because it had steel strings.

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:55.790
And it was one of the few of these
older Elizabethan instruments

00:11:55.790 --> 00:11:57.880
that did not have gut strings.

00:11:57.880 --> 00:12:02.000
So it had a really bright, sort
of a cutting tone in the ensemble.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.780
And then of course you
have the standard lute.

00:12:04.780 --> 00:12:07.090
So two viols, treble
and bass, flute,

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:11.220
and then three plucked
instruments, the bandora,

00:12:11.220 --> 00:12:12.520
he cittern, and the lute.

00:12:12.520 --> 00:12:16.260
And this became a fairly
standard consort.

00:12:16.260 --> 00:12:21.570 position:56%
Within Elizabethan times, there were
of course many variations on that.

00:12:21.570 --> 00:12:25.350
Any number of instruments could
be a part of a broken consort,

00:12:25.350 --> 00:12:27.490
as long as they weren't
just all the same thing.

00:12:27.490 --> 00:12:31.630
There were often virginals or
other keyboard instruments,

00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:36.000
and you'll hear some virginal music
in the program that is put on,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.580
that we're going to listen to.

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:44.230
But this particular core group
of instruments is what is thought

00:12:44.230 --> 00:12:46.810
of as that particular consort.

00:12:46.810 --> 00:12:49.360
And this comes, it's
sort of solidified

00:12:49.360 --> 00:12:52.420
in syntagma musicum of Praetorius.

00:12:52.420 --> 00:12:58.780
This is the standard for modern,
modern players who are looking back

00:12:58.780 --> 00:13:02.040
and trying to figure out what, how
these instruments work together

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:04.190
and how music was performed.

00:13:04.190 --> 00:13:05.700
This particular treatise, which is

00:13:05.700 --> 00:13:08.450
in three volumes, is
critical for that.

00:13:08.450 --> 00:13:13.930 position:56%
Another place in which the broken
consort appears, and you get a sense

00:13:13.930 --> 00:13:18.750
of what exactly it was for, is in
an anonymous painting from 1596,

00:13:18.750 --> 00:13:21.580
called the birth and
death of Sir Henry Unton.

00:13:21.580 --> 00:13:27.860
And this is a strange
painting that is

00:13:27.860 --> 00:13:30.590
in the portrait gallery in Britain.

00:13:30.590 --> 00:13:34.300
And after Henry Unton
died in the 1590s,

00:13:34.300 --> 00:13:38.890
his wife commissioned an unknown
artist to paint this piece

00:13:38.890 --> 00:13:45.400
that depicted him, death, and an
angel on either side of his head

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:49.130
and he's writing because he
was a scholar and a statesman.

00:13:49.130 --> 00:13:54.110
And then within the painting are
ten different themes from his life,

00:13:54.110 --> 00:13:56.510
important things that
happened to him.

00:13:56.510 --> 00:13:59.970
So it's kind of a biography
of this person.

00:13:59.970 --> 00:14:11.030
And one of these scenes, which is
here, depicts a group of musicians

00:14:11.030 --> 00:14:13.450
at an Elizabethan banquet.

00:14:13.450 --> 00:14:17.270
And you see people eating
here, there's a room

00:14:17.270 --> 00:14:19.390
with people playing cards
and they have [inaudible],

00:14:19.390 --> 00:14:22.040
and they're sitting
around this table

00:14:22.040 --> 00:14:23.750
with a little kid who's
doing something,

00:14:23.750 --> 00:14:25.780
I'm not sure why he's there.

00:14:25.780 --> 00:14:29.540
Then down here, you have another
group as similar to this group,

00:14:29.540 --> 00:14:32.580
but obviously they're people,
and they're in the main sort

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:34.320
of dinning hall where
this is happening.

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:38.510
And there are these weird sort
of red-faced people walking next

00:14:38.510 --> 00:14:40.890
to each other, and I'm not
sure what that's about.

00:14:40.890 --> 00:14:45.090
There's a whole procession of these
guys, some candles, these guys,

00:14:45.090 --> 00:14:49.050
some candles, and then some
more oddly-dressed folks

00:14:49.050 --> 00:14:51.870
who I assume are a theater troop
because they're going up here

00:14:51.870 --> 00:14:57.580 position:56%
by the table to, I assume, entertain
people, and be much smaller

00:14:57.580 --> 00:14:59.160
in scale than the actual table.

00:14:59.160 --> 00:15:03.580
So, that's a [laughing]
just something that happens

00:15:03.580 --> 00:15:04.900
in paintings at that time.

00:15:04.900 --> 00:15:10.850
But anyway, so you have this
particular view of a broken consort

00:15:10.850 --> 00:15:17.170 position:56%
in action, and you have the flute,
the two viols, the cittern, Pandora,

00:15:17.170 --> 00:15:22.930
and lute in a circle, there
and then again, up at the top.

00:15:22.930 --> 00:15:29.380
So there is that, and then there is
the first book of consort lessons

00:15:29.380 --> 00:15:35.160
of Thomas Morley, which was
a very important publication

00:15:35.160 --> 00:15:42.540
for consort songs, and
consort music in the time.

00:15:42.540 --> 00:15:44.780
And this publication, which says,

00:15:44.780 --> 00:15:47.660
if you probably can't read
it, if you're very far back.

00:15:47.660 --> 00:15:50.260
But it says the first book
of consort lessons made

00:15:50.260 --> 00:15:54.360
by diverse exquisite authors for
six instruments to play together,

00:15:54.360 --> 00:15:57.560
the treble lute, the pandora,
the cittern, the bass voile,

00:15:57.560 --> 00:15:59.530
the flute, and the treble voile.

00:15:59.530 --> 00:16:00.860
And it goes on to say things

00:16:00.860 --> 00:16:03.700
about how gentlemanly they'll
be when they play them.

00:16:03.700 --> 00:16:10.840
But this particular publication
is what inspired the consort group

00:16:10.840 --> 00:16:15.300
to put on the concert
that we are going to hear.

